I"Š)<h4 id="core-sample">Core Sample</h4>

<p><img src="http://localhost:4000/assets/img/project/coreSample/c1.png" alt="img1" />
<em>æ ¸èŠ¯æ¨£æœ¬ææ¡ˆæ¨¡æ“¬åœ– Rendering of Core Sample Proposal</em></p>

<p>By the year 2100, all of the worldâ€™s biomes have endured chaotic shifts in climate: rising sea levels, changing weather patterns, and decades of mass extinction have rendered Earth less hospitable for more living species than during any era since the last ice age (IPCC 2018). In â€œCore Sample,â€ we respond to several speculative narratives of ecological collapse, like E. E. Cummingsâ€™ poem â€œpity this busy monster, manunkind,â€ and Jean Gionoâ€™s allegory â€œLâ€™homme qui plantait des arbres,â€ imagining a portal that opens upon the future. In a distant time and place, hundreds of years beyond our catastrophic moment, natural life cohabitates with the new and exotic lifeforms that emerge after the holocene. Unlike typical core samplesâ€”archives of deep time that reveal the worldâ€™s intractable pastâ€”our core sample summons a future of fragility and potential, where the balance of life depends on a single, elemental seed.</p>

<p>â€œCore Sampleâ€ takes the form of a two-meter-wide column of light. At its center, above a fiberglass shell containing wires, tubes, and pumps, levitates an acorn, glowing by virtue of its own inductive power. The shell is covered in a layer of soil, which supports an ecosystem of both living and pneumatic species. The longer â€œCore Sampleâ€ remains installed in an environment, the more its own ecosystem blends with the native flora around it. We imagine installations in different biomes, of increasing durations, each a unique inquiry into the relationships endemic between nature and technology, plantlife and humanity. As such, â€œCore Sampleâ€ explores what Natasha Myers has called the planthropocene, â€œan aspirational epoch in which people learn to collaborate with the plantsâ€ (Myers 2016), and offers the viewer a glimpse into the enigmatic future of our natural worldâ€”and our place within it.</p>

<p><img src="http://localhost:4000/assets/img/project/coreSample/c2.jpg" alt="img1" /></p>

<p><em>(æ‹æ”æœ€çµ‚ç‰ˆçš„å½±ç‰‡å‰ï¼Œæˆ‘å€‘å…ˆåœ¨åŠ å·å¤§å­¸æŸå…‹èŠåˆ†æ ¡çš„æ ¡åœ’è£¡æ¸¬è©¦å®‰è£ï¼Œä»¥äº†è§£æ‰€éœ€çš„å™¨æèˆ‡æ™‚é–“ã€‚æœŸé–“é‡åˆ°è¨±å¤šå­¸ç”Ÿå¥½å¥‡ç¶“éï¼Œå‰›å¥½å½¢æˆä¸€å€‹å°å‹å±•ï¼Œå¤§å®¶åœååœ¨åœŸä¸˜çš„å‘¨åœåˆ†äº«æ„Ÿæƒ³ã€‚The test install in UC Berkeley Campus)</em></p>

<p>Responding to  â€œCore Sampleâ€ illustrates the power of a single seed to redeem an environment and give new life to even the most impoverished wasteland.</p>

<p><img src="http://localhost:4000/assets/img/project/coreSample/c3.jpg" alt="img1" />
<em>ä¸Šæ–¹çš„æ¨¹æœ¨å‰›å¥½å½¢æˆä¸€å€‹æ‹±å½¢ï¼Œç½©è‘—æ ¸èŠ¯æ¨£æœ¬</em></p>

<p>The primary technical requirement for displaying â€œCore Sampleâ€ is a constant power source. It needs one 120V 15A circuit (or 230V 10A) or sustainable energy source such as solar panels and batteries if connection to the grid is not available. The footprint of the piece is a diameter and height of two meters each, so viewers can walk around it. It needs a hanging structure above for hanging the top ring light (less than 3kg)</p>

<p>We have also shown â€œCore Sampleâ€ in the museum context. The Exhibition in 2020 Digiwave Tech Art Festival in Kaohsiung, Taiwan and the showcase of Taiwan Ministry of Culture Arts and Technology: Creative Innovation and Counseling Project at C-Lab Taipei, Taiwan have given the opportunity for the audience to experience the piece in person in the civil setting.</p>

